            <span class="bold-gray"><a title="http://www.jasoncollins.org" href="http://www.jasoncollins.org" rel="nofollow">Jason Collins</a> </span> writes:
                            </div>
        </div>
                  <div class="comment">
                                <div class="blog">
                                    <div class="blogcommenter">
            <p>Can a similar argument be made regarding income taxes? To rephrase your sentence:</p>

<blockquote>Because income taxes discourage human capital formation, they also cause other tax revenues to be lower. If there's less human capital formation, workers are less productive. If they're less productive, the government collects less tax revenue from them.
</blockquote>

<p>This raises the question of what the optimal tax rates are when you consider these trade-offs across all of the forms of capital and effort.</p>
                                    </div>
                                </div>

